Got it — authorized pentest/internal program/own-company context, intranet-only with no internet egress, and a mixed/unknown stack. The no-egress constraint is the most important variable: it rules out passive recon APIs, cloud OAST, and anything that phones home. I'll build the methodology around that. Diving in now.

Your internal web application pentest methodology report is ready. It covers air-gapped toolbox preparation, self-hosted OAST setup, and Active Directory-integrated recon workflows tailored for intranet-only targets with no internet egress. The report spans nine phases—from initial reconnaissance with nmap/masscan/NetExec through content discovery, vulnerability scanning with offline Nuclei, manual exploitation via Burp with NTLM/Kerberos, authentication-specific testing including NTLM relay and Kerberoasting, secrets hunting across internal Git and SMB shares, and local-first reporting—plus a Day-1 quick-start command reference and cross-cutting hygiene checklist. Key tooling includes Impacket, ntlmrelayx, Kerbrute, puredns, katana, jsluice, kiterunner, ffuf, custom Nuclei templates, and self-hosted interactsh, with detailed offline-mode configurations throughout.
